<header class="page-header">
  <h1 class="title">About</h1>
  <p class="lede">The Atlas is a public Zettelkasten — a digital garden of atomic notes that link to one another and grow over time.</p>
</header>

<div class="content sobre">

  <h2>What it is</h2>
  <p>Each note tries to say <em>one</em> thing — an idea, a concept, an argument — as clearly as I can manage at the time. The notes don't live in isolation: they link to one another, and meaning comes from those links. The whole is neither a book nor a blog, but a network that keeps thickening: a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zettelkasten">Zettelkasten</a> open to reading.</p>

  <h2>The process</h2>
  <p>I write the notes in <a href="https://obsidian.md/">Obsidian</a>, in plain text (Markdown). Each note is a file whose name is its title; links are made with <code>[[wikilinks]]</code>. When I save, the site rebuilds itself — <a href="https://www.11ty.dev/">Eleventy</a> turns the files into pages and publishes them. The map, the backlinks and the search are all generated from the notes themselves: there is no database, only text files that outlive the software.</p>

  <h2>Maturity</h2>
  <p>Ideas aren't born finished. Each note carries a stage that says where it stands:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Seedling</strong> — rough, an intuition or jotting still to be worked.</li>
    <li><strong>Budding</strong> — taking shape, structured but still under revision.</li>
    <li><strong>Evergreen</strong> — mature, revised, settled enough to leave alone.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>It's the logic of the <a href="https://maggieappleton.com/garden-history">digital garden</a>: thinking in public, rather than only publishing what is already finished.</p>

  <h2>Why</h2>
  <p>Writing forces you to think. Putting the notes in public forces you to think better — and to expose the links that would otherwise stay in my head. The Atlas is above all a working instrument: the ground where I cross what occupies me — the <strong>philosophy of technology</strong> and <strong>health informatics</strong> — and test whether the ideas hold up when said out loud.</p>

  <h2>Colophon</h2>
  <p>Built with <a href="https://www.11ty.dev/">Eleventy</a>; typeset in <a href="https://fraunces.undercase.xyz/">Fraunces</a> and <a href="https://github.com/googlefonts/literata">Literata</a> with <a href="https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Archivo">Archivo</a> and <a href="https://www.jetbrains.com/lp/mono/">JetBrains Mono</a> (all OFL); colours from the <a href="https://github.com/tiagojct">Try-Works</a> design system (Moby-Dick, ch. 96); map in <a href="https://d3js.org/">D3</a>; search with <a href="https://pagefind.app/">Pagefind</a>. No cookies, no intrusive tracking. The code and the notes live in an open repository.</p>

</div>
